			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">In a game (provided that the sampling rate is not too high), any N163 channel could be easily used to play 4-bit PCM data with volume control by having the channel set to a 4-step wavetable, with all steps of that wavetable always being equal. To avoid potential noise coming from the little time delay between writing two wavetable bytes to change the volume, the frequency could be set to 0 and if that's not really possible, then set to such a low amount that the PCM update would happen too fast, which should also reset the wave phase to 0 just to make sure.<br /><br />Alternatively (and this may be potentially much less CPU-intensive and better in pretty much every way) the same trick could be used to play samples as on the Gameboy. The wavetable serves as a buffer, and is set to a desired frequency, while the 163 also generates IRQs at the same rate, so that when the wavetable cycles through once, the CPU rewrites the wavetable with the next chunk of data. This only requires attention from the CPU when a new data chunk is needed (sadly rules out melodic samples because of OAM DMA in a game)<br /><br />I'd also definitely generate pulse waves with different widths on the fly if I were to write an N163 sound engine. (Or use the trick where two flipped and slightly detuned sawtooth waves cancel out into a PWM sweeping pulse wave)</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

